@Vaer

Thank you.
Exquisite!

@Thomas
Ditto.
Just...Ditto.

@Matt

So, ditto ditto.

I get you.

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight

You were misinformed. Here is what Lincoln himself wrote:

<a href="https://presidentlincoln.illinois.gov/exhibits/online-exhibits/gettysburg-address-everett-copy" target="_blank">https://presidentlincoln.illinois.gov/exhibits/online-exhibits/gettysburg-address-everett-copy</a>/

@HeathieJ

I must have missed the post you mention. Take care of yourself! MRI, etc. 

🫂

@Beth and Andrzej

Thank you and no worries, it was buried a few comments down below my main comment, more as an aside.

I appreciate your kind thoughts!!  ❤️☺️❤️

@Steve L
I think we had this conversation before! 
The HALLS you mention are not that usual in UK; but I will try to remember the term for the future.

@Jeff Z

I did.
And I still don’t.

@Steve L
Your logic is of course impeccable. That said, for some of us, knowledge doesn't percolate that easily. 
I know there is an English Women's soccer team, I even know their name is Lionesses, and that they won something some time. That's all. I don't now if I should know more.

@Jane Wheelaghan

You're forgiven...but the US women's team has been a powerhouse for a long time; in fact the most successful women's national soccer teams since the 90s, so they have been on news interview shows forever.  I don't mean to insult the English ladies, but I'd bet they're not as prominent, especially since the men's game is so much more prominent there.

So you might not be familiar with names on either team, but Americans who are aware of the world around them probably can name the stars of the US team.

@Rich in Atlanta
I know nothing about basketball, but the phrase "quadruple double" seemed familiar, like it had been an entry before.

I guess Mr. Boddily has upped the bar by using rebuses for the double letters, and grid art.

@Linda Jo

"(...)I neither know nor care what QUADRUPLE DOUBLE means in basketball."

Ha! Love it! My feelings exactly.

@Jon H
@Mean Old Lady

OCCAM's name is sometimes spelled Ockham, so when I first put in OCAM, I thought, "Is there another alternate spelling of his name?  Could be!"
And I first thought the revealer was going to be "the triPLE DOUBLE", so it took a while to correct it.

@RDJ Same for me, I was 10 minutes under my average for Thursday and usually have a tough time picking up "hidden" themes and rebuses. 

In this case I was totally wrong - a couple of crossers led me to believe the constructor had just decided to omit all double letters but it ended up serving me well.  The 'CC' in MECCAS was the last square to fall for me.

Better to be lucky than good for me in this case.

@A James
You got DOOKed.

Don't feel bad, I did too.

@Joe
To add to the confusion, the farmer really isn't squeezing the UDDER, but the TEATS ...and these days, it's a no-hands operation anyway.
One learns over time that the NYT crossword crew is largely (or entirely) composed of City Folk who perhaps don't think that some of these niceties matter anyway.  Bless their hearts.

@Mean Old Lady
All the slings and arrows regularly hurled at “city folks”, god forbid anyone reviled “country folk” in the same way.
Yes, it’s the New York Times. More subways and operas than hayrides and hootenannies.

@John Peil

Isn't it wonderful when you get that feeling? 🙌 Congratulations!! 

Next up: getting that feeling when you make what feels like a wild stab... and it turns out to be correct! 🎉

@Ben

It's Thursday.  There's going to be a gimmick.  Figuring it out is half the fun.

And did you not notice that the revealer clue at 50-Across concluded "… or a feature shared by 3-, 6- and 9-Down"?

@Brendon Ruggiero
Don't hurt yourself when you "get it" and feel like doing the head-desk thing.
Anytime you feel indignant like that, think, "AHA! You rascally constructor, you can't fool ME!"

@Brendon Ruggiero

Please please *read the column* before complaining about the puzzle! It's the content directly below the button you clicked to get to the comments. 

Hint: It's called a *rebus*...

@Chelsea Owen

The CC in ME(CC)AS *is* one of the four doubles in A(LL)A(CC)E(SS)PA(SS). 

BUFFS and UDDERS are not thematic in nature.

@William Schrader

Yep, I shuddered at that one. But given that teats are part of the udder, as a nipple is part of a breast, it works for a crossword, if not in real life.
But it's like describing a nipple piercing as a "breast piercing". A little more anatomical specificity is both appropriate and welcome, to all concerned.

@drsophila

Omg, this!! Can we just pin this comment at the top of the page every Thursday (and some Sundays)?

Well, at least I can take a screenshot and refer to it from time to time to calm my nerves.  :)

@drsophila

Oh, if it were only this simple.

I tell myself that if I don't like someone's comment, I can just keep scrolling, but I find it hard to take my own advice.

@Grant
@Andrzej

I don't have any complaint with people complaining. I enjoy hearing different opinions, and I do my own fair share of complaining. It's just when they become so redundant and predictable.  And the anti-rebus crowd seems to take it as a personal affront that the Times would even consider such an egregious violation of the rules.

@Barbara

I too got the "something's amiss" at the end of my solve.  You can see where I went wrong in the next comment.
But, of course, I can't tell you where you might have gone wrong.

@Barbara

Same here. Finished rather quickly but not getting the music. I’ve combed through it three times now and can’t spot a mistake. 

I have all the rebuses entered correctly. I think.

@NYC Traveler I had aMEN and spent a little while before I figured out it was OMEN
That clinched the win and CUED the music. 

I liked this puzzle bc it was fun, fair and I had no look-ups.

@Calhouri

Using a laptop, I can get to rebus on the NYT web site quite easily by positioning the cursor on the square, then hitting the Esc key.  This opens a field you can input multiple letters.

If you're using the app, I don't know what to tell you.

@Chris

Yes, Vaer's suggestion was very good too.

It's a little like a the batting team stealing pitch signs, but all is fair in love, war, baseball, and crosswords.

@Ben

Yeah, you didn't get the puzzle exactly right.  The software would accept one M, but the true answer was MM, a rebus.

These types of misunderstandings would be much less frequent if people read at least some of the Wordplay column before rushing to the comments.
